
<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-frustums" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Frustums</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the volume of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres. Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a frustum as a cone or pyramid that is cut parallel to its base, removing the top portion, resulting in a truncated shape with two parallel bases. Distinguish between cone frustums and pyramid frustums.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the formula <m>V = \frac{1}{3}\pi h(r^2 + R^2 + Rr)</m> to calculate the volume of a frustum of a cone. Calculate the slant height using the Pythagorean theorem.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving frustum volumes such as buckets, lampshades, flowerpots, and jerrycans. Convert volumes between cubic centimetres and litres.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-frustums.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-frustums.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Frustum Volume Lab</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in pairs or small groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    Calculators, rulers or measuring tapes, water and a measuring jug, real plastic buckets or flowerpots (frustum-shaped), worksheets for dimensions and calculations
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, ensuring students measure accurately. Ask probing questions: <q>What shape is this? How is it different from a cone?</q> For struggling groups: <q>Let us measure together. What is the top radius? What is the bottom radius?</q> For early finishers: <q>How would the volume change if the top radius doubled?</q> Guide students to articulate that a frustum is a cone with the top sliced off.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>What shape is a frustum?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How is a frustum different from a cone?</p></li>
                        <li><p>What real-world objects have frustum shapes?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How can we find the volume of a frustum?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How does the measured volume compare with the calculated volume?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            Identify 2<ndash/>3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>


<activity xml:id="auto_xbd9z92c">
