    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing the Frustum Volume Formula</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> A frustum is the same as a cone. <alert>Clarification:</alert> A frustum is a cone with the top sliced off, creating two circular bases.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> The formula is the same as the cone formula. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The frustum formula includes both radii: <m>r^2 + R^2 + Rr</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> The height is the slant height. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The height is the perpendicular distance between the two bases, not the slant height.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> I can use the diameter instead of the radius. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The formula uses the radius. If you have the diameter, divide by 2.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Walk through the worked example on the board step-by-step. Emphasise finding the slant height first using the Pythagorean theorem, then calculating the volume. Allow students to attempt practice problems independently. Circulate to check working and provide support.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_i2ulaq56">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_enm2no86">
                    A frustum of a cone has a top radius of 4 cm, a bottom radius of 8 cm, and a height of 10 cm.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_8ge7mj7k">
                   a. Find the slant height of the frustum.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1xjbns72">
                   b. Find the volume of the frustum.
                </p>
                <image width="25%">
        <latex-image label="frustum-full-cone-example">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw the bottom base (larger circle)
                \draw (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6);
                \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);
    
                 % Draw the top base (smaller circle)
                \draw (-1,3) arc (180:360:1 and 0.3);
                \draw[dashed] (1,3) arc (0:180:1 and 0.3);
    
                % Draw the slant height lines for frustum
                \draw (-2,0) -- (-1,3);
                \draw (2,0) -- (1,3);
    
                % Draw slant height lines for full pyramid (to the apex)
                \draw (-2,0) -- (0,6);
                \draw (2,0) -- (0,6);
                \draw (-1,3) -- (0,6);
                \draw (1,3) -- (0,6);

                % Draw height lines
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,6); % Total height H
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,3); % Height of the frustum h

                % Labeling the diagram
                \node[left] at (0,4) {$h$}; % Total height
                \node[above] at (0.5,2.9) {$4 cm$}; % Small radius
                \node[below] at (-1.2,0) {$ 8 cm$}; % Large radius
                <!-- \node[left] at (0,1.5) {H}; -->
                \draw[dashed] (-2,0) --(0,0);
                \draw[dashed] (0,3) --(1,3);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_follr2qo">
                    Using the Pythagoras theorem, the slant height <m>\ell</m> is given by:
                    <md>
                      <mrow>  \ell = \amp \sqrt{8^2 + 10^2}</mrow>
                      <mrow> = \amp 12.80 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Slant height <m>\ell = 12.80\, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_gfm9v4rv">
                    Finding the volume.
                  <m>V = \frac{1}{3}\pi h (r^2+ R^2 + Rr)</m>
                  <md>
                    <mrow> V = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 10\, \text{cm} \times (4^2 + 8^2 + (8\times 4))\, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac {22}{21}  \times 10\, \text{cm} \times (16\, \text{cm}+64\, \text{cm}+32\, \text{cm}) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{220}{21} \times 112\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 1173.33 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                  </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Exit Ticket</title>
                <p>
                    Students complete questions 3<ndash/>5 individually.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key (Teacher Reference)</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>Square pyramid frustum: <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times h \times (a^2 + A^2 + aA)</m>, where <m>h = 12</m> cm, <m>a = 6</m> cm, <m>A = 12</m> cm. <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times 12 \times (36 + 144 + 72) = 1008\,\text{cm}^3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>900 = \frac{1}{3}\pi h(36 + 100 + 60)</m>. Solve for <m>h</m>: <m>h \approx 4.37\,\text{cm}</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>V = \frac{1}{3}\pi \times 30 \times (15^2 + 20^2 + 15 \times 20) = 24{,}347\,\text{cm}^3 \approx 24.35</m> litres.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

        <p xml:id="auto_70x8adof">
            <m>\textbf{Exercise}</m>
        </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hdf2dzh6">
            1. Shell petrol station has the shape of an inverted right circular cone of the radius 7 m and height 15m 
            dug underground in the shape of the figure shown below. Calculate the volume of petrol it holds when full in litre.
        </p>
        <image width="30%">
        <latex-image label="example-petrol-station-frustum">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
               % Define a light purple color
                \definecolor{lightpurple}{RGB}{230,230,250}
                
                % Top ellipse (wider, now at the top)
                \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                
                % Bottom ellipse (narrower, now at the bottom)
                \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                
                % Side surfaces
                \draw[thick] 
                    (-3,5) -- (-1.5,0) -- (1.5,0) -- (3,5) -- cycle;
                
                % Outline of side lines
                \draw[thick] (-3,5) -- (-1.5,0);
                \draw[thick] (3,5) -- (1.5,0);
                \draw[thick] (-3,5) -- (3,5);
                \draw[thick] (-1.5,0) -- (1.5,0);
                
                % Height line (dashed)
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,5);
                
                % Dimension lines and labels
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3.5,0) -- node[left] {15m} (-3.5,5);
                \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3,5) -- node[above] {7m} (3,5);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
        
        
        
      <p xml:id="auto_hdl4gisc">
        2. A frustum of a cone has a base radius of 8 cm, a top radius of 5 cm, and a height of 12 cm.
        Find its volume.
      </p>
      <image width="30%">
        <latex-image label="frustum-full-exercise-cone">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw the bottom base (larger circle)
                \draw [thick](-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6)--cycle;
                \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.6);
    
                 % Draw the top base (smaller circle)
                \draw[dashed]  (-1,3) arc (180:360:1 and 0.3)--cycle;
                \draw[dashed] (1,3) arc (0:180:1 and 0.3);
    
                % Draw the slant height lines for frustum
                \draw[dashed]  (-2,0) -- (-1,3) --cycle;
                \draw[dashed]  (2,0) -- (1,3)--cycle;
    

                % Draw height lines
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,3); % Total height H
                \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,3); % Height of the frustum h

                % Labeling the diagram
                <!-- \node[left] at (0,4) {$x$}; % Total height -->
                \node[above] at (0.5,2.9) {$5 cm$}; % Small radius
                \node[below] at (-1.2,0) {$ 8 cm$}; % Large radius
                \node[left] at (0,1.5) {12cm};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_08eaueuz">
        3. A square pyramid is cut into a frustum, where the original height was 18 cm, and the truncated top part has a height of 6 cm. The base side length is 12 cm, and the top side length is 6 cm.
        Find the volume of the frustum.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_pyjhoz19">
        4. A frustum of a cone has a volume of 900 cm³, a base radius of 10 cm, and a top radius of 6 cm. Find its height.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_fnydkpxv">
       5. An A improvised jerrycan shaped like a frustum of a cone with a top radius of 20 cm, a bottom radius of 15 cm, and a height of 30 cm.
         How many liters of water can the bucket hold?
      </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-measured frustum models with labelled dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use frustums with simple dimensions for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li><p>Allow use of calculators for all calculations.</p></li>
                <li><p>Break down the formula into steps: calculate <m>r^2</m>, <m>R^2</m>, <m>Rr</m>, add them, multiply by <m>h</m>, multiply by <m>\pi</m>, divide by 3.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to verify their formula with water measurements.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to explain the relationship between frustums and cones.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with different dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge students to find the volume when only the diameters and height are given.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Challenge students to derive the formula using the difference between two cones.</p></li>
                <li><p>Explore real-world applications: buckets, lampshades, flowerpots, jerrycans.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate the relationship between radii, height, and volume.</p></li>
                <li><p>Apply the concept to frustums of pyramids with square or rectangular bases.</p></li>
                <li><p>Solve optimisation problems: Given a fixed volume, what dimensions minimise the surface area?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity <mdash/> Designing a Bucket or Flowerpot:</alert> In groups, design a frustum-shaped bucket for a specific purpose (e.g., water storage, planting flowers). Decide on dimensions, calculate the volume. If the bucket needs to hold 10 litres, determine what dimensions would work. Compare different designs and present findings with diagrams and calculations.
        </p>
    </axiom>

